																		SO YOU WANT TO BE A CONCEPT REVIEWER?
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zyn" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1404533); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1404533&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610251590" alt="Zyn" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1404533)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zyn" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1404533); return false;" >Zyn</a></span> <span class="odate time_1546326955 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">01 Jan 2019 07:15</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4105023">
									

<p>Welcome to the Ideas Critique Forum!</p>
<p>This is where newbies and veterans alike come to shop their concepts around until they have something that they're ready to write into a full draft (or use to revamp an existing draft). This is where reviewers come into play, since we have a lot of widely read community members who remember thousands of SCPs!</p>
<p>If you'd like to help authors polish up their ideas and potentially think up the Next Best Thing, here are a few things to keep in mind!</p>
<p>1. <strong>Tell the author what you liked (or didn't like) about their idea, and <em>why</em>.</strong></p>
<p>2. <strong>Tell the author what you think they should fix or do next, and <em>why</em>.</strong></p>
<p>That's pretty much it!</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Click&nbsp;to&nbsp;show&nbsp;some&nbsp;more&nbsp;detailed&nbsp;instructions</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">hide</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<ul>
<li><strong>Give the author a direction to follow!</strong>
<ul>
<li>Just saying &quot;needs work&quot;/&quot;needs more&quot;/&quot;has potential&quot; and leaving it at that is vague and unhelpful because the author doesn't know what specifically needs work or has potential.</li>
<li>Just saying &quot;I like this a lot&quot; / &quot;I don't like this&quot; is also too vague. What specific parts were good and can be kept after edits? What parts are weaker and can be trimmed?</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Make sure you know what the community wants!</strong>
<ul>
<li>SCPs don't need to be dangerous or scary or capable of ending the world to be successful. Be familiar with the current site standards and what the community is expecting in an article of quality.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Be aware of forum activity!</strong>
<ul>
<li>If you're not inclined to write a thorough review (i.e., covering concept, execution, a few examples of specific fixes, and so on), please hold off on making the first post so a more experienced reviewer can address the thread first. That gives the author a more accurate gauge of the potential overall audience response.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>For some reading to get the creativity engine running, consider:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/essays-on-style">http://www.scp-wiki.net/essays-on-style</a> (a bunch of authors talk about how/where they get their ideas!)</li>
<li><a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/ideation">http://www.scp-wiki.net/ideation</a> (a bunch of different ways to explore ideas!)</li>
<li><a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/things-what-do-a-thing-an-essay-on-things">http://www.scp-wiki.net/things-what-do-a-thing-an-essay-on-things</a> (a bunch of ways to handle the classic &quot;thing that does a thing&quot; SCP formula!)</li>
</ul>
<p>We've also got the <a href="/reviewers-spotlight-archive">Reviewers' Spotlight</a>, which shows off great pieces picked by prominent reviewers for front-page fame!</p>
<p>Remember, reviewers can shape a concept from &quot;meh&quot; to &quot;holy #%$@!!&quot; You speak for a portion of the audience when you respond to an author, and play a key role in the development of the site's material and canon. Best of luck with all your reviewing endeavors!</p>

							</div>

								
